        <outline text="Game Theory #GT" _note="https://workflowy.com/#/5b960e3137a6">
            <outline text="Complete (Symmetric) Information Games #h">
                <outline text="Classical Results on Matrix (Zero-Sum) Games #h " _note="#zero-sum #matrix">
                    <outline text="#todo clarify payoff &gt; value"/>
                    <outline text="Definition and Notations #slide">
                        <outline text="$$A$$ -- square, real matrix of dimension $$n$$"/>
                        <outline text="$$x, y$$ -- mixed strategies (probability vectors $$x,y \in {\mathbb R}^n$$ with $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i x_i=1$$ and $$0\le y_i\le 1$$, $$\sum_i y_i=1$$)"/>
                        <outline text="$$v=v(A)$$ -- value of the game, defined as $$v:=\max_x \min_y xAy = \min_y \max_x xAy $$"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Matrix Games #slide">
                        <outline text="These are two-person, zero-sum finite games $$G=(X,Y,A)$$ where ">
                            <outline text="$$X$$ and $$Y$$ are the sets of strategies for the different players "/>
                            <outline text="$$A:X\times Y \mapsto R$$ is the payoff function. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Zero-sum game: one player wins what the other player loses"/>
                        <outline text="We use a matrix to represent the payoff function"/>
                        <outline text="The first (row) player plays a row action"/>
                        <outline text="The second (column) player plays a column action"/>
                        <outline text="Without loss of generality, we can assume that all entries of $$A$$ are positive, as adding #todo "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Best Response #slide">
                        <outline text="Any player will want to maximise her payoff, which means ">
                            <outline text="maximising $$xA$$ if $$x$$ is Player 1's strategy,"/>
                            <outline text="minimising $$Ay$$ if $$y$$ is Player 2's strategy. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="With her best response, a player will want to maximise what she gets out of the other player's move.">
                            <outline text="The best response for Player 1 is to assume maximum damage caused by the other player, and then to try mitigating this as much as possible: $$ \max_x \min_y xAy =: v^{+}$$. "/>
                            <outline text="The best response for Player 2 is to assume Player 1 seeks maximum gain, and then to limit this as much as possible: $$\min_y \max_x xAy =: v^{-}$$."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Value of Game #slide">
                        <outline text="$$v^{-}$$: __lower value__"/>
                        <outline text="$$v^{+}$$: __upper value__"/>
                        <outline text="Using elementary mathematics, it can be seen that $$v^{-} \le v^{+}$$."/>
                        <outline text="Min-max Theorem">
                            <outline text="In the setting of a matrix game, these two values can be seen to be the same: $$v^- = {v^+}$$."/>
                            <outline text="This is non-trivial: von Neumann's Theorem."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Definition: the __value__ of the game is then $$v(A):=\max_x \min_y xAy = \min_y \max_x xAy $$"/>
                        <outline text="The value is unique, as identical to best responses"/>
                        <outline text="Any strategy $$x^*, y^*$$ satisfying $$x^*Ay^* = v$$ is called __optimal__. There may be several such $$x^*, y^*$$."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Nash Equilibrium for Matrix Games #slide">
                        <outline text="We say that $$(x^*, y^*)$$ is a NE strategy profile iff">
                            <outline text="$$xAy^* \le v = x^*Ay^* \;\forall x$$"/>
                            <outline text="$$x^* Ay \ge v = x^*Ay^*\;\forall y$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Note that one can show for zero-sum games that any combination of different optimal strategies yields an equilibrium strategy. "/>
                        <outline text="Often, NE are not mentioned in the context of zero-sum games."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Computation of Value #slide "/>
                    <outline text="Principle of Indifference #slide "/>
                    <outline text="Linear Algebra Approach #slide "/>
                    <outline text="Linear Programming Approach #slide "/>
                    <outline text="References "/>
                </outline>
