        <outline text="Applications of Game Theory to Security" _note="https://workflowy.com/#/929e463e968d&#xA;#GT #ch2  #small #big #decision #h #sg-field">
            <outline text="Introduction #slide ">
                <outline text="Security games analyse attacker-defender security scenarios using game theory,"/>
                <outline text="This is highly appropriate under the assumption that both attacker and defender are rational entities. #sg-field #motivation"/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Complete Information Security Games #h #complete-info-sg-field" _note="#GT #security #small #big #cloud #single-target #two-target #ch3">
                <outline text="Motivation #slide ">
                    <outline text="Complete information security games assume the mutual knowledge of strategies by both attacker and defender. #complete-info-sg-field #motivation"/>
                    <outline text="In real-world scenarios, this could correspond to a situation where the attacker, through reconnaissance, might gain some knowledge through insider information or information leakage. #motivation"/>
                    <outline text="The defender might be aware of potential attackers and their motivation through security assessment and risk analysis. #motivation"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="DECISION-MAKING SECURITY GAMES ($$n$$ PLAYERS) #h #decision ">
                    <outline text="Economics and Security Games - Basic Equations #slide ">
                        <outline text="$$p$$ - Exogenous probability of attack"/>
                        <outline text="Expected utility function of defender under attack with probability $$p$$ is $$u = b - p \cdot c_a - c_d$$ where $$c_a$$ is the cost due to assets under attack and $$c_d$$ is the defense cost."/>
                        <outline text="More specifically, $$u = b - p (1 - \sigma(\gamma)) L - \kappa(\gamma)$$"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="CLOUD PROVIDER DECISION-MAKING SECURITY GAMES #decision"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Incomplete Information Games #h ">
                <outline text="Specific Signalling Game #h ">
                    <outline text="@Moghaddam2015 #review #GT #cloud #signal">
                        <outline text="Aim of the paper: #slide ">
                            <outline text="They design a signalling game for helping a Client (C) to decide whether to trust a Service Provider (SP) or not"/>
                            <outline text="They obtain the trust level as an output of their game."/>
                            <outline text="Trust level or whether to trust or not?!"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="This signalling game is nested and can be decomposed into two games: #slide ">
                            <outline text="Attacker-Defender (AD) game &quot;Avoiding Game&quot;">
<outline text="Scenario">
    <outline text="A cloud service provider is using resources in order to fulfil the client's request"/>
    <outline text="An attacker attacks resources that are in use."/>
    <outline text="Initial scenario: there are only two resources in the cloud, but then later there are $$N$$ (Extended-AD game)."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Discussion">
    <outline text="How will \theta be published? In other word, if the cloud is a black box, would we still know the values in the normal form (utility function)?"/>
    <outline text="How will \theta be computed and utility function is unknown?"/>
    <outline text="What does parametric (parametric normal form) mean in this context?"/>
</outline>
<outline text="********Game******** ">
    <outline text="Type">
        <outline text="Static complete information parametric normal form game"/>
        <outline text="Not a perfect information game, so the actions are not known to the players"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Description">
        <outline text="Service Provider picks a resource for requested service, attacker chooses a resource to compromise"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Players">
        <outline text="Cloud Service Provider (SP)"/>
        <outline text="External attacker"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Strategies">
        <outline text="Cost/benefit functions are not explicitly given"/>
        <outline text="********Strategies:******** ">
            <outline text="S_{SP} = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)"/>
            <outline text="S_A = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Analysis of Game">
    <outline text="Nash Equilibria">
        <outline text="Results:">
            <outline text="There is no pure strategy Nash equilibrium"/>
            <outline text="They compute the mixed Nash equilibrium for the cases $$N = 2$$ and the general case for the assumption that the attacker only chooses one resource to attack."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="\theta is an output of the AD game (The value of \theta determines 2 different possible games for the signalling game)"/>
        <outline text="A probability \theta is mathcalculated from the mixed NE, indicating the likelihood that the cloud resources are compromised"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
