                <outline text="SPECIFIC BAYESIAN SECURITY GAMES #h ">
                    <outline text="The author in \cite{} design a signalling game for helping a Client (C) to decide whether to trust a Service Provider (SP) or not. They obtain the trust level as an output of their game. This signalling game is nested and can be decomposed into two games: Attacker-Defender (AD) Game (Avoiding Game) and service provider-client signalling-game."/>
                    <outline text="In the first game, a cloud service provider is using resources in order to fulfil the client's request. Meantime, an attacker attacks resources that are in use. As an initial scenario, there are only two resources in the cloud, but then later there are $$N$$ (Extended-AD game). The game is a 2-player static complete information parametric normal form game with imperfect information -- actions are not known to the players. The players are the cloud SP and the external attacker. In the game, the service provider picks a resource for the user's requested service while the attacker chooses a resource to compromise."/>
                    <outline text="For each game, there is a utility function that would compute the cost and benefit for each player. However, in this model, the functions are not explicitly given. On the other hand the following are the strategies for the SP and attacker respectively: $$S_{SP} = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)$$ and $$S_A = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)$$."/>
                    <outline text="In the AD-game, there is no pure strategy. However, the mixed Nash equilibrium (NE)  is computed for the cases $$N = 2$$ and the general case for the assumption that the attacker only chooses one resource to attack. A probability $$\theta$$ is then mathcalculated from the mixed NE, indicating the likelihood that the cloud resources are compromised. Hence, $$\theta$$ is an output of the AD-game where the value of $$\theta$$ determines 2 different possible games for the signalling game."/>
                    <outline text="The service provider-client signalling game can be decomposed into SP-client game and SP-client signalling (SPC) game."/>
                    <outline text="In the service provider-client signalling game there are two players: the cloud SP and the user. The user might face either a compromised cloud or a safe one. The game consists of two dynamic games: one  for the safe cloud and the other for the compromised cloud. It is similar to the type of AD-game, but it is not a static game. In addition, the client does not know if the SP is compromised or not."/>
                    <outline text="Discussion">
                        <outline text="AD-GAME!! How will $$\theta$$ be published? In other word, if the cloud is a black box, would we still know the values in the normal form (utility function)? How will $$\theta$$ be computed and utility function is unknown? What does parametric (parametric normal form) mean in this context?"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
