                            <outline text="**TWO-TARGET  **($$n=2$$)">
<outline text="RESOURCE ALLOCATION (SEARCH) GAME #h">
    <outline text="Motivation"/>
    <outline text="********Notations******** ">
        <outline text="$$t_1, t_2$$ -- targets (asset $$a_1$$ and $$a_2$$) #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
        <outline text="$$r$$ -- resource, covering either $$t_1$$ or $$t_2$$ #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
        <outline text="Strategies">
            <outline text="$$S_D = \{\mbox{defend } t_1, \mbox{defend } t_2\} = \{s^{t_1}_D, s^{t_2}_D\}$$"/>
            <outline text="$$S_A = \{\mbox{attack } t_1, \mbox{attack } t_2\} = \{s^{t_1}_A, s^{t_2}_A\}$$"/>
            <outline text="All pure strategy profiles:">
                <outline text="$$s_{11} = (s^{t_1}_D, s^{t_1}_A)$$, #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
                <outline text="$$s_{22} = (s^{t_2}_D, s^{t_2}_A)$$, #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
                <outline text="$$s_{12} = (s^{t_1}_D, s^{t_2}_A)$$, #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
                <outline text="$$s_{21} = (s^{t_2}_D, s^{t_1}_A)$$, #GT #security #small #two-target"/>
            </outline>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Utilities"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="An equilibrium analysis helps with a complete classification of (certain types of) small security games.">
                            <outline text="https://www.economics.utoronto.ca/osborne/2x3/tutorial/NEIEX.HTM"/>
                            <outline text="We explain how to derive the existence of a mixed NE strategy in the case of a generic one-target small security game."/>
                            <outline text="********We consider the following payoff matrix \[\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \hline &amp;amp; \textbf{Attack} (q) &amp;amp; \textbf{Not Attack} (1 - q) \\\hline \hline \textbf{Defend} (p) &amp;amp; a_1, a_2 &amp;amp; b_1, b_2 \\ \hline \textbf{Not Defend} (1 - p) &amp;amp; c_1, c_2 &amp;amp; d_1, d_2 \\ \hline \end{array}\]where $$a_i$$, $$b_i$$, $$c_i$$ and $$d_i$$ $$(i \in \{1, 2\})$$ are the utility functions of the two players for the different pure strategies.******** "/>
                            <outline text="********Denote $$p$$ the probability that the defender decides to take the action of defending so that \[ p = P[D \mbox{ defends}] \] and hence, \[ P[D \mbox{ not defend}] = 1 - p. \]******** "/>
                            <outline text="********Correspondingly, we set \[ q = P[A \mbox{ attacks}] \]as the probability of an attack occurring on the defender. We can now state the utility of the defender for a mixed strategy while being attacked as \[ u^{a}_{D} = p a_1 + (1-p) c_1, \] and that of the attacker not attacking \[ u^{-a}_{D} = p b_1 + (1-p) d_1. \]******** "/>
                            <outline text="More generally, if we have a completely mixed strategy with probabilities $$p$$ and $$q$$, for the actions of the defender and attacker respectively, we can express the expected utility of the defender as \[\begin{equation} u_{D} = p [q a_1 + (1-q) b_1] + (1-p) [q c_1 + (1-q) d_1] \end{equation}.\]  (@equation1)"/>
                            <outline text="********On the other hand, we obtain the expected attacker utility \[\begin{equation} u_{A} = q [p a_2 + (1-p) c_2] + (1-q) [p b_2 + (1-p) d_2] \end{equation}. \] (@equation2)******** "/>
                            <outline text="In order to maximise the utility function, we differentiate equations (@equation1) and (@equation2) with respect to $$p$$ and $$q$$ respectively to obtain \[ \begin{eqnarray}  \frac{d}{dp} u_D&amp;amp;=&amp;amp;q a_1 + (1-q) b_1 + (-1) q c_1 + (-1)(1-q) d_1 \nonumber \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;amp; q(a_1 - c_1 - b_1 + d_1) + b_1 - d_1   \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\] and  \[\begin{eqnarray}  \frac{d}{dq} u_{A}&amp;amp;=&amp;amp;  p a_2 + (1-p) c_2 + (-1)( p b_2 + (1-p) d_2)   \nonumber \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;amp;p a_2 + c_2 - p c_2 - p b_2 - d_2 + p d_2  \nonumber \\ &amp;amp;=&amp;amp; p(a_2 - c_2 - b_2 + d_2) + c_2 - d_2.   \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]"/>
                            <outline text="Equating to 0, this yields \[ p^{*} = \frac{d_2 - c_2}{(d_2 - c_2) + (a_2 - b_2)}\] (@p_star) and\[q^{*} = \frac{d_1 - b_1}{(d_1 - b_1) + (a_1 - c_1)}.\] (@q_star)"/>
                            <outline text="********The expected utilities of this game are $$u_D|_{p=p^{*}}$$ and $$u_A|_{q=q^{*}}$$.******** "/>
                            <outline text="********The solutions are both best responses to any strategy taken by both players which is equivalent to a Nash optimal strategy.******** "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="We can apply this to specific settings, motivated by real-world scenarios."/>
                        <outline text="Small security games for application scenarios #h ">
                            <outline text="CVSS GAMES">
<outline text="Basic CVSS Game [Cyber Science 2017 Paper] #h" _note="https://www.dropbox.com/s/3hupz06gbfht5y6/Our%20Basic%20CVSS%20Game%20%5BCyber%20Science%202017%20Paper%5D%20-%20WorkFlowy.pdf?dl=0">
    <outline text="******Notations &amp;amp; Definitions ****** ">
        <outline text="******$$\kappa$$ -- defense cost (direct cost)****** "/>
        <outline text="******$$\bar{V} = \langle V_C, V_I, V_A \rangle$$ -- asset value vector****** "/>
        <outline text="******$$\alpha$$ -- relates to attacker's profile (strength)****** "/>
        <outline text="******$$\bar{\mu}_{Imp} = \langle \mu_{Imp, C}, \mu_{Imp, I}, \mu_{Imp, A}\rangle$$ -- CVSS Impact score in vector representation****** "/>
        <outline text="******$$\mu_{Exp}$$ -- CVSS Exploitability score****** "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="**Further Work**">
        <outline text="******#todo Use more  sophisticated defender cost framework (consider indirect costs -- colateral damage?) ****** "/>
        <outline text="******#todo considerable novelty: expand to incomplete information game, using Bayesian framework, enabling the use of environmental CVSS scores****** "/>
        <outline text="******#todo include additional CVSS subscores (cf vulnerability factors in [Panaousus GameSec 14]****** "/>
        <outline text="******#todo Address issue with the ease of attacker acceptance****** "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="**Game Type**">
        <outline text="******A 2-person static complete-information &quot;security game&quot;****** "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="******Discussion****** ">
        <outline text="******This is a very simple model, although similar to most of the other game models published in the  context of vulnerability patching  [#todo list other papers]. ****** "/>
        <outline text="******The idea of an attacker profile is a novelty, extending the idea of a organisational cyber security profile as presented in [Panaousis GameSec 14]. ****** "/>
        <outline text="******Attacker might not easily accept this model, as his expected utility is zero (note: not many papers talk about this!)****** "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="******Utility Matrix \[\begin{array}{ | c | c | c | } \hline &amp;amp; s^{a}_A &amp;amp; s^{-a}_A \\ \hline s^{d}_D &amp;amp;  - \kappa, - \alpha \cdot {\mu_{Exp}}^{-1} &amp;amp;  -\kappa,  0 \\ \hline s^{-d}_D &amp;amp;  -\bar{\mu}_{Imp} \cdot \bar{V},  \bar{\mu}_{Imp} \cdot \bar{V} - \alpha \cdot {\mu_{Exp}}^{-1}&amp;amp;  0,  0 \\ \hline \end{array}\] ****** "/>
    <outline text="******Summary****** ">
        <outline text="******Aim: improve vulnerability scoring through the use of game theory****** "/>
        <outline text="**Main contributions:**">
            <outline text="******Design novel utility functions based on using CVSS metrics****** "/>
            <outline text="******Report on application potential for a cyber tool (CAESAIR)****** "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="**Nash Equilibrium Analysis**">
        <outline text="******There exists no pure NE (#todo add justification)****** "/>
        <outline text="**Optimal Expected Utilities**">
            <outline text="******$$u_D|_{p=p^{*}}=-\kappa$$  ****** "/>
            <outline text="******$$u_A|_{q=q^{*}} = 0$$****** "/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="**Optimal Mixed NE Strategies**">
            <outline text="******$$p^{*} =  1 - \frac{\alpha \cdot {\mu_{Exp}}^{-1}}{\bar{\mu}_{Imp} \cdot \bar{V}}$$****** "/>
            <outline text="******$$q^{*} = \frac{\kappa}{\bar{\mu}_{Imp} \cdot \bar{V}}$$****** "/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
</outline>
