            <outline text="Small Complete Information Security Games #h ">
                <outline text="Generic Game #slide ">
                    <outline text="Focusing on the single software asset that contains a vulnerability, we define a __single-target small security game__ in normal form through the following payoff matrix"/>
                    <outline text="$$\begin{array}{ | c | c | c | }  \mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A}\rightarrow &amp; a &amp; \overline{a} \\ d &amp;  - c^{\mathcal{D}}, - c^{\mathcal{A}}&amp;  -c^{\mathcal{D}},  0 \\  \overline{d} &amp;  -l^{\mathcal{D}},  l^{\mathcal{D}}- c^{\mathcal{A}} &amp;  0,  0 \end{array}$$ " colorLabel="3"/>
                    <outline text="where the rows correspond to the pure strategies available to the defender $$\mathcal{D}$$ and the columns are the attacker's pure strategies. Here  we assume that the attacker's benefit equals the loss of the defender. "/>
                    <outline text="This game has been studied in the past (see e.g. \cite{@Samarji2015}) and is suitable for our scenario which is based on a single asset vulnerability assessment. It is not the specialisation of a big security game."/>
                    <outline text="The following assumption seem reasonable in a realistic setup: "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Game Analysis #slide ">
                    <outline text="The analysis of this presented security game is not difficult, it can be shown that there are no pure Nash equilibrium strategies as [..] and hence a closed-form expression exists \cite{} for determining the values $$p^{*} = \frac{c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}} = 1 - \frac{c^{\mathcal{A}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$ and $$q^{*} = \frac{c^{\mathcal{D}}}{l^{\mathcal{D}}}$$ forming a mixed Nash equilibrium strategy $$(s_D^{*}, s_A^{*})$$ where $$p^*$$ and $$q^*$$ are the probability of defense and attack respectively. "/>
                    <outline text="This will be the underlying method to compute our attack likelihood in this scenario, based on $$q^*$$."/>
                    <outline text="One verifies that the expected utilities in this case are $$ u_D^{*} = -c^{\mathcal{D}} $$ and $$ u_A^{*} = 0 $$."/>
                    <outline text="[TODO: derive these results by applying the algebraic framework from the previous section]"/>
