            <outline text="\label{linear-algebra-section} #h ">
                <outline text="Notations #slide " complete="true">
                    <outline text="We first introduce some notations used in the remainder of the paper." complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="We define $$A$$ and $$B$$ to be real matrices of dimension $$m\times n$$. A \emph{matrix pencil} is an expression of the form $$A-\lambda B$$ where $$\lambda$$ is an indeterminate.  We say that $$A-\lambda B$$ is a \emph{regular} matrix pencil if the involved matrices are square and $$\det(A-\lambda B)  \neq 0$$ for all but a finite number of values of $$\lambda$$. Otherwise, the pencil is  \emph{singular}.  % #todo Explain eigenvalues and eigenvectors -- all eigenvectors are assumed to be normalised. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="More information about the theory of matrix pencils can be found e.g. in \cite{Gantmacher}. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="We will be interested in matrices of the form $$A-\lambda$$. Our preferred notation for these will be matrix pencil representation of the form $$A-\lambda E$$ where $$E$$ is a square matrix of matching dimension with all entries set to 1.  Furthermore let $$e$$ be a column vector consisting only of entry 1. The dimension of $$e$$ which will be clear from its context. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="Given a bimatrix game $$(A,B)$$ with payoff matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$, a mixed strategy for Player 1 (the row player) is a real vector $$x$$ satisfying $$0\le x_i\le 1$$, with all components summing up to 1. A mixed strategy for Player 2 (the column player) is a real vector $$y$$ satisfying the same properties. " complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="All vectors will be column vectors and the row vector corresponding to $$x$$ will be written as $$x^\top$$." complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="A \emph{best response} to $$y$$ is a strategy $$x$$ of Player 1 that maximizes his expected payoff $$x^\top Ay$$. A best response to $$x$$ is a mixed strategy $$y$$ of Player 2 that maximizes her expected payoff $$x^\top By$$. A Nash equilibrium is then a pair of mutual best responses." complete="true"/>
                    <outline text="Finally, for the particular case of $$B=-A$$, we obtain the matrix (zero-sum) game $$A$$. In this paper, we will denote  $$V=V(A)$$ the value of this game, defined as $$V:=\max_x \min_y xAy = \min_y \max_x xAy $$. % [ #todo Change notation]" complete="true"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="In this section, we develop our algebraic  framework. After briefly reviewing related work in the literature, we present the main contribution of this paper: sufficient algebraic conditions for the direct construction of game solutions. Finally we illustrate our approach using an example. % #signpost" complete="true"/>
                <outline text="% Algorithms for 2-Player Games%" colorLabel="5">
                    <outline text="A large body of research investigating the design of algorithms for solving bimatrix games exists. Most methods are based on linear techniques, an overview of such approaches is given e.g. in \cite{@Stengel2002}. [ #todo More recent refs] " complete="true"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="% Security Games % #slide ">
                    <outline text="For the special case of security games as introduced in \cite{@Kiekintveld2009}, more specialised methods have been developed."/>
                    <outline text=", exploiting properties specific to these types of games and reducing the bimatrix game to a matrix (zero-sum) game \cite{@Korzhyk2011a}. Other transformation techniques are given in \cite{}. By relaxing the assumption of algebraic independence of  the matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$, algorithmic game analysis is simplified. In \cite{}, the authors show how to compute optimal Nash Equilibria if the game matrices are linked by an affine transformation. [ #todo More recent refs] The notion of strategical equivalence as defined in \cite{@Moulin1978} can also be characterised in terms of algebraic relations however it does not seem applicable to arbitrary security games \cite{@Korzhyk2011a}. "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="% Direct properties % #slide ">
                    <outline text="In this paper we are interested in linking algebraic properties of two \emp{independent} game matrices $$A$$ and $$B$$ and optimal solutions of the game. Our motivation is the use of such a relationship for explicitly solving security games. It will turn out that they are applicable to the kind of security games we are interested in. "/>
                    <outline text="There is little stated about such direct relationship in the literature. ">
                        <outline text="The results of \cite{@Weil1968} and \cite{ShapleySnow1950} [#todo @luluwah Find citation], applicable to matrix games, were the initial inspiration for the work in this Section and Theorem \ref{} is a generalisation. Theorem \ref{} then extends this to bimatrix games. The work in \cite{bimatrix}, although not using the concept of matrix pencils, #todo "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="%The Bimatrix Game Case % #h " colorLabel="5">
                    <outline text="A First Result #slide ">
                        <outline text="We now extend our results from the previous section to square bimatrix games. "/>
                        <outline text="**Theorem**. Given a bimatrix game $$G=(A,B)$$, assume the matrix pencils $$A-\lambda E$$  and $$B-\lambda E$$ are both regular, with real eigenvalues $$\mu_A$$ and $$\mu_B$$. Let $$x_{\mu_B}$$ a nonnegative left eigenvector of $$B-\lambda E$$ with respect to $$\mu_B$$ and denote $$y_{\mu_A}$$ a nonnegative right eigenvector of $$A-\lambda E$$ with respect to $$\mu_A$$. Then $$(x^*,y^*) = (x_{\mu_B}$$, $$y_{\mu_A}$$) is a Nash Equilibrium strategy profile of the game $$G$$ and $$(\mu_A, \mu_B)$$ are the corresponding optimal payoffs of both players. #theorem @non-zero-sum-regular-theorem:here" colorLabel="3"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="A Lemma #slide ">
                        <outline text="The proof of the theorem will be aided by the following lemma. It exhibits a special case arising where there exists a strategy of one player to there exists a best response of the other player with maximal support. "/>
                        <outline text="\begin{lemma}">
                            <outline text="\label{best-response-lemma}"/>
                            <outline text="Following the notations as in the theorem, we have for a nonnegative left eigenvector $$x_{\mu_B}$$ that for all Player 2 strategies $$y$$ it holds $$x^\top_{\mu_B} B y = \mu_B $$. Similarly, a nonnegative right eigenvector $$y_{\mu_A}$$ satisfies $$x^\top A y_{\mu_A} = \mu_A$$ for all Player 1 strategies $$x$$." colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="\end{lemma}"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Proof  #slide ">
                        <outline text="Assume that $$x^{\top}_{\mu_A}\ge 0$$ is a left eigenvector, associated with the eigenvalue $${\mu_A}$$ of the regular matrix pencil $$A-\lambda E$$. This implies" colorLabel="4"/>
                        <outline text="\begin{equation}\label{left-nullspace-eq}">
                            <outline text=" $$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A}(A-{\mu_A} E)=0. $$" colorLabel="4"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="\end{equation}"/>
                        <outline text="Due to the normalisation property $$\sum x_{{\mu_A},i}=1$$ we have $$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A} E = x^{\top}_{\mu_A} ee^{\top}=e^{\top}$$ so that equation (\ref{left-nullspace-eq}) implies " colorLabel="4">
                            <outline text="$$ x^{\top}_{\mu_A} A = {\mu_A} e^{\top}. $$" colorLabel="4"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The second property for a right eigenvector $$y_{\mu_B}$$ can be shown very similarly. From this, the lemma follows. " colorLabel="4"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Proof [of Theorem \ref{non-zero-sum-regular-theorem}] #slide ">
                        <outline text="Let $$y_{\mu_A}$$ be nonnegative right eigenvector of $$A-\lambda E$$ with respect to the eigenvalue $$\mu_A$$. From Lemma \ref{best-response-lemma} we deduce that $$y_{\mu_A}$$ is a best response to any Player 1 strategy $$x$$, in particular to  $$x=x_{\mu_B}$$. Likewise,  denote $$x_{\mu_B}$$ a nonnegative left eigenvector of $$B-\lambda E$$. We obtain that  $$x_{\mu_B}$$ is a best response to Player 2 strategy $$y=y_{\mu_A}$$. Hence these strategies are mutual best responses and by definition optimal mixed Nash Equilibrium strategies with payoffs $$\mu_A$$ and $$\mu_B$$ as required." colorLabel="4"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="%The Matrix Game Case % #h " colorLabel="5">
                    <outline text="Starting point of our investigation was the observation that there are sufficient condition for the existence of optimal strategies and value of zero-sum games, expressed in terms of algebraic properties of the game matrix $$A$$.  % ">
                        <outline text="\begin{theorem}[Shapley, 1950] Assume the square matrix $$A$$ is nonsingular and $$e^\top A^{-1}e \neq 0$$. Then the game with matrix $$A$$ has value $$V(A)=V=1/e^\top A^{-1}e$$ and optimal strategies $$x=Ve^\top A^{-1}$$ and $$y=VA^{-1}e$$, provided both $$x$$ and $$y$$ are nonnegative.\end{theorem}"/>
                        <outline text="The proof of this theorem only requires elementary algebra, and is a special case of our proof of Theorem \ref{}. "/>
                        <outline text="The benefit of this result is that it computes the game value, provided $$v \neq 0$$ under some assumptions that do not seem too restrictive. % #todo "/>
                        <outline text="\begin{theorem}">
                            <outline text="\label{weil-theorem}"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="[Weil, 1968] If $$A$$ has the real eigenvalue $$\lambda$$ corresponding to nonnegative eigenvectors $$x$$ and $$y$$, then $$v(A-\lambda I)=0$$ and $$x$$, $$y$$ are optimal for the game $$A-\lambda I$$. " complete="true"/>
                        <outline text="\end{theorem}"/>
                        <outline text="Whilst this theorem might be applicable more often than the previous, it does mostly compute the value of a different game. "/>
                        <outline text="It turns out that a natural setting for properties such as those stated in the last two theorems is that of regular matrix pencils, their associated (generalised) eigenvalues and eigenvectors. "/>
                        <outline text="expressed as generalised eigenvectors of an associated regular matrix pencil.  "/>
                        <outline text="A zero-sum matrix game can be directly solved if $$\deg(\det A - \lambda E) &gt; 0$$, i.e. the matrix polynomial vanishes identically in $$\lambda$$. "/>
                        <outline text="The following theorem generalises Shapley's theorem as it is also valid for $$v=0$$ and at the same time it improves Weil's theorem as it characterises the value of the same game (rather than a different one)."/>
                        <outline text="\begin{theorem}">
                            <outline text="\label{zero-sum-regular-theorem}"/>
                            <outline text="Assume the matrix pencil $$A-\lambda E$$ is regular, with a real eigenvalue $$\mu$$ corresponding to nonnegative left and right eigenvectors $$x_\mu$$ and $$y_\mu$$. Then the value of the game $$G(A)$$ is $$v(A)=\mu$$ and $$(x_\mu$$, $$y_\mu$$) is an optimal strategy profile. " colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="\end{theorem}"/>
                        <outline text="We will defer the proof of this theorem, as it can be obtained as a special case of our proof for Theorem \ref{}. "/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="ARCHIVE">
                <outline text="Typically, when maintaining software assets, system administrators will over time encounter the need for vulnerability management. Due to the accumulation of available patches for a potentially large number of assets, they need effective strategies for identifying those patches that are critical. A common practice that is adopted in real system scenarios is based on vulnerability scoring which provides effective means of ranking vulnerabilities by their severity. A common approach for vulnerability scoring is based on a numerical score (or metric) function $$\mu:v \rightarrow {S}$$ that is computed for the individual vulnerability, where $$\mathcal{S}$$denotes the set of valid scores."/>
                <outline text="[CVSS] The Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) provides an open framework for such vulnerability scoring, based on metrics capturing the individual, intrinsic characteristics of a software vulnerability. CVSS has been developed by the Forum of Incident Response and Security Teams (FIRST), its current version is v3.0, published in 2015, and it is the de facto vulnerability scoring standard adopted by many organisations, implemented as part of tools and openly available both in terms of documentation and as scoring data linked to the publicly available CVE vulnerability database. " _note=" ">
                    <outline text="% An alternative representation consists of a vector providing a compressed textual representation, reflecting the values used to derive the score."/>
                    <outline text="Overall, CVSS v3.0 assesses the severity of software vulnerabilities through three Metric Groups: Base, Temporal and Environmental. The CVSS Base Score $$\mu_{B}$$ represents the intrinsic and fundamental characteristics of $$v$$ that are independent of time and specific user environments. The Base score can then be refined by defining additional scores in order to more accurately reflect the risk posed by the vulnerability to an asset:"/>
                    <outline text="\begin{itemize}">
                        <outline text="\item Temporal -- metrics which reflect the characteristics of the vulnerability $v$ that change over time."/>
                        <outline text="\item Environmental -- representing the characteristics of $v$ that are unique to the user's environment."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="\end{itemize}"/>
                    <outline text="Generally, the Base and Temporal metrics are specified by the organisation, while the environmental metric depends on the end-users." _note=" "/>
                    <outline text="In the latest version CVSS 3, the scoring of vulnerabilities has improved -- e.g. Heartbleed is now scored higher than before."/>
                    <outline text="This would make a transition from a vulnerability-focused approach to a risk-based scoring system."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Starting point of this paper is previous work on enhancing the use of CVSS for vulnerability scoring with the help of game theory and the growing evidence \cite{} that vulnerability scoring has also limitations and needs possible remedies. The main problem with vulnerability scoring is that it is possible for two different vulnerabilities to have the same score, although they both have individual characteristics. Whilst this is impossible to prevent in general, a careful design of the individual scoring functions should at least take this problem into account." _note=" "/>
                <outline text="Game Theoretic Design of Vulnerability Scoring Functions">
                    <outline text="% RELATED WORK %">
                        <outline text="To our knowledge, the use of Game theory for vulnerability scoring has not been addressed in the literature."/>
                        <outline text="Most work is on likelihood assessment, the process of establishing the probability of an attack occurring (\cite{@Samarji2015},\cite{@Kanoun2009}) which appears, in general, to be a challenging and elusive task \cite{@Tripwire2016}.  % "/>
                        <outline text="One way of conducting likelihood assessments is to assume that the interaction between potential cyber attackers and system administrators (who act as defenders) can be modelled as a non-cooperative game, where both players act rationally, seeking to optimise their expected payoffs. The game can then be analysed by making some assumptions on the players' strategies, which yield an expected optimal strategy from which system administrators should be able to make a decision regarding \emph{vulnerability patching}. "/>
                        <outline text=" and, together with vulnerability scoring, might be seen as a way to implement risk scoring which has been suggested to be more effective than vulnerability scoring alone \cite{@Reguly2013}\fmanos{check citation.}. Likelihood assessment "/>
                        <outline text="In \cite{@Samarji2015}, the authors have a similar methodology, focusing on the attacker's perspective inspired by game theory, using a very similar game, but in addition they capture concurrent and simultaneous attacks and also model return of investment equations. We extend the simplified version of their model by making explicit use of CVSS metrics for the design of a more realistic and practically oriented game.  %"/>
                        <outline text="In \cite{@Gianini2015} the authors investigate the use of game theory as an alternative to CVSS-only vulnerability patching strategies. The initially studied game is a a two-target security game, also known as a search game in the literature. The game theoretic analysis is used as a filter to narrow down the number of vulnerabilities that need to be considered for patching, e.g. using traditional vulnerability scoring techniques such as CVSS. "/>
                        <outline text="This is a contrast in our approach where we use CVSS scoring information to improve the accuracy of our game theoretic utility function, hence making our model more accurate and suitable for real world scenarios."/>
                        <outline text="% #todo [review some more papers, including \cite{@Kanoun2009}, \cite{@Bistarelli2006} and \cite{@Gianini2015}]  %"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="% DESIGN %"/>
                    <outline text="% EVALUATION %">
                        <outline text="% #signpost"/>
                        <outline text="In  this section we compare and evaluate the scoring functions as defined by the CVSS v2.0 and v3.0 base score as well as our game theoretical scoring function. "/>
                        <outline text="\begin{itemize}&#xA;">
                            <outline text="\item In CVSS v2.0, the equation defining the base score is $$\mu_{CVSSv2} = k_1 \cdot \mu_{Imp} + k_2 \cdot \mu_{Exp} - k_3$$ where $$k_1 = 0.71$$, $$k_2 = 0.47$$ and $$k_3 = 1.76$$ assuming $$\mu_{Imp} \neq 0$$. "/>
                            <outline text="\item CVSS 3.0 defines the base score as $$\mu_{CVSS.v3} = \lceil \min\{1.08 \cdot (\mu_{Imp} + \mu_{Exp}),10\} \rceil$$"/>
                            <outline text="\item Our basic GT score is $$\mu_{GT}=\alpha(10-\mu_{Exp})/\mu_{Imp}$$\footnote{We will have to choose $$\alpha$$ such that the range of the final scoring function is between 0 and 10. We will be able to determine this after having calculated the score distribution, see below.}"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="\end{itemize}&#xA;"/>
                        <outline text="While both CVSS equations use linear combinations of impact and exploitability, the game theoretical equation is non-linear. " _note=" "/>
                        <outline text="A theoretical evaluation of these functions can be done by analysing the score distribution of all valid output metrics. For each scoring function, we create a graph, plotting the number of occurrences of values $$\sigma = \mu(v')$$ with $$\sigma \in [0,10]$$ for which exists a (hypothetical) vulnerability $$v'$$. The range of valid input subscore is determined from the possible values of the subscores included in the impact and exploitability scores as follows: "/>
                        <outline text="\begin{itemize}">
