            <outline text="Secure Data Distribution #h1">
                <outline text="Notations">
                    <outline text="$$s&lt;p$$ -- secret, where $$p$$ is a prime number"/>
                    <outline text="$$s_i$$ -- a share of the secret $$s$$, with (unique) identifier $$i$$"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Concepts"/>
                <outline text="Advantages/Disadvantages"/>
                <outline text="Protocol Stages">
                    <outline text="Dealing"/>
                    <outline text="Distribution "/>
                    <outline text="Combining"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Basic Techniques in the Literature">
                    <outline text="Shamir Secret Sharing">
                        <outline text="Shamir -- Polynomial evaluation and interpolation"/>
                        <outline text="$$f(x) = s + \sum_{l=1}^{k-1}a_{l}x^{l}$$ where $$a_{l}$$ random elements of $$F_p$$ -- the Shamir polynomial "/>
                        <outline text="Within the secret sharing protocol follow 3 stages: share creation, share distribution and share combining."/>
                        <outline text="Share creation. ">
                            <outline text="Choose $$n$$ distinct values $$x_{1},\ldots, x_{n}$$"/>
                            <outline text="Compute shares as $$s_i = (x_{i},f(x_{i}))$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Distribution/Dealing"/>
                        <outline text="Share Combining">
                            <outline text="From any coalition of size $$k$$   $$(x_{i_1},\cdots , x_{i_k})$$ and $$(f\left ( x_{i_1}\right ), \cdots , f\left ( x_{i_k}\right ))$$ we can reconstruct $$f$$ (and hence $$s = f\left ( 0 \right )$$) through interpolation."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Ramp">
                        <outline text="Ramp -- Use all coefficients"/>
                        <outline text="$$f(x) = \sum_{l=0}^{k-1}s^{(l)}x^{l}$$ where $$s=s^{(0)}||\ldots||s^{(k-1)}$$ are the secret data, seen as elements of $$F_p$$ -- a generalisation of the Shamir polynomial, storing data in all coefficients"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Blakeley -- Intersecting hyperplanes, in fact a specific instance of ramp [Blakley]"/>
                    <outline text="Rabin' Information Dispersal">
                        <outline text="Sharing of information/data matrix A with n device in order to achieve confidentiality, redundancy &amp;amp; …"/>
                        <outline text="Rabin -- IDA, expanding secret vector to a matrix, improving capacity. Shamir could be seen as special case "/>
                        <outline text="Distribution is implemented by sending each row of  and row of  the result of the matrix multiplication."/>
                        <outline text="Given the confidential information">
                            <outline text="$$a = (a_{1},\cdots, a_{t}) , ( a_{t+1},\cdots, a_{2t}) , \cdots , ( a_{N-t+1},\cdots, a_{N}) = a^{(1)}, a^{(2)}, \cdots, a^{(m)} $$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="where">
                            <outline text=" $$m = \lceil \frac{N}{t} \rceil$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="and">
                            <outline text="$$A =\left [ \ ^{t}a^{(1)} \left | \cdots \right |\ ^{t}a^{(m)} \right ]$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Construct a matrix $$X$$ such that any submatrix consisting of $$k$$ rows forms an invertible matrix, denoted by $$X^{(k)}$$. "/>
                        <outline text="Here k is a threshold value, meaning the number of shared items needed to reconstruct A."/>
                        <outline text="Dispersal stage: ">
                            <outline text="Compute $$Y$$ as  $$X \cdot A = Y \qquad \left ( \ast \right )$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Reconstruction:   ">
                            <outline text="the shares are then the concated rows of A and Y "/>
                            <outline text="It follows from $$\left ( \ast \right )$$ that $$X^{(k)} \cdot S = Y^{(k)} $$"/>
                            <outline text="So $$S= \left [ X^{(k)} \right ]^{(-1)}\cdot Y^{(k)}$$"/>
                            <outline text="Can write this in matrix / vector notation: $$X \cdot a = y$$ where">
<outline text="$$X = \begin{pmatrix} x_{1}^{0} &amp; x_{1}^{1} &amp; \ldots &amp; x_{1}^{k-1}\\ x_{2}^{0} &amp; x_{2}^{1} &amp; \ldots &amp; x_{2}^{k-1}\\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots\\ x_{n}^{0} &amp; x_{n}^{1} &amp; \ldots &amp; x_{n}^{k-1} \end{pmatrix}$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="In order to find $$S$$, we need the first entry of the vector $$a = X^{-1}\cdot y$$"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Krawcyc -- IDA + Encryption "/>
                </outline>
